E. COLI EHEC - USA (32): (NORTH, SOUTH CAROLINA) O157, COUNTY FAIR
*******************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Mon 15 Oct 2012
Source: Gaston (NC) Gazette [edited]
http://www.gastongazette.com/number-of-e-coli-cases-now-at-38-1.30094


The number of people infected by _E. coli_ [O157] after attending the Cleveland County Fair nearly doubled over the weekend. By 1 pm Mon 15 Oct 2012, 38 cases in the region were being investigated by the NC Department of Health and Human Services as potentially being infected with the deadly strain of bacteria.

The breakdown of cases includes 18 in Cleveland County, 7 in Gaston, 9 in Lincoln, 1 in Catawba, 1 in Union and 1 case in each York and Cherokee counties in South Carolina. The 1st death from the outbreak came late Friday night, 12 Oct 2012.

22 children and 16 adults have fallen ill from exposure to _E. coli_ [O157] bacteria. State and local health officials have been investigating the incidents to determine a common denominator. Thus far, the single thread is attending the Cleveland County Fair. State health officials identified the strain of bacteria in 2 cases as coming from animal fecal matter. But not all of the sick fair attendees walked through the petting zoo, much less touched the animals.

According to Professor Clifford Grimsley, a microbiologist at Gaston College, just attending the fair could cause substantial risk of infection.

[Byline: Diane Turbyfill]

